POLIOMYELITIS UPDATE (49): PAKISTAN (KHYBER PAKHTUNKHWA)
********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 17 Jun 2019 3:28 PM
Source: Urdu Point and End Polio Pakistan [edited]
https://www.urdupoint.com/en/pakistan/nih-confirms-fresh-polio-case-from-district-b-646775.html
http://www.endpolio.com.pk/polioin-pakistan/polio-cases-district-wise-2019


The National Institute of Health (NIH) Islamabad [Mon 17 Jun 2019] notified a fresh polio case from district Bannu [Khyber Pakhtunkhwa] taking the total count of polio cases in district Bannu to 9 [?8], in Bannu division to 14, overall in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa to 18, and total of 24 in the country so far during 2019.

Coordinator Emergency Operation Centre (EOC) Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Capt. (R). Kamran Ahmed Afridi in a statement said that wild poliovirus has been isolated from stool sample of a 17-month-old boy, resident of Bachaki Market, UC Jani Khel, Tehsil subdivision Wazir, Bannu district, whose father refused to administer anti polio vaccine as well as essential routine immunization to him.

Afridi said that "such cases emerged time and again to prove the fact that refusing anti-polio vaccine to our children put them and other children in the surroundings at risk of being paralyzed."

Kamran Ahmed Afridi said, "as virus is in circulation in the region therefore it would continue to target unimmunized children."

He appealed to parents and caregivers to save their children from paralysis and ensure administering anti-polio vaccine to their children during special case response campaign launched today [17 Jun 2019] in district Bannu, Laki Marwat, DIKhan, Tank, North Waziristan, South Waziristan, Shangla, Buner, and District Torghar.

[Byline: Faizan Hashmi]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the End Polio Pakistan website, the addition of this newly confirmed case brings the national total number of WPV1 associated polio cases in Pakistan to 24, with 8 cases reported from Bannu district and 18 overall in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (including Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Tribal Districts) (http://www.endpolio.com.pk/polioin-pakistan/polio-cases-district-wise-2019).

Unfortunately it is a similar tale, with parental refusal to vaccinate, so the child suffers and the virus keeps finding susceptibles to continue its transmission in the country.

For a map showing districts of Pakistan, see https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/pak215_pakistan_districts_v5_a0_20181203.pdf.

HealthMap/ProMED map of Bannu, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6524486,42679. - Mod.MPP

